    <% main_text: 'Challenge #2: Alternate Method for Critical Communications When Wireless Communications Systems are Overloaded or Unavailable.', %>
    <% detail_paragraphs: ['In today&rsquo;s day and age, smartphones ownership is outpacing landline phones ownership across the United States (see CDC study https://www.cdc.gov/nchs/data/nhis/earlyrelease/wireless201705.pdf). &nbsp;Cell phones are increasingly the mechanism that residents use to get help during emergencies, provide updates to loved ones on their status and whereabouts during major events (via social media and the like) , and even get critical alerts from government officials on safety precautions, avoiding areas, and shelter locations. &nbsp;These wireless networks, are more and more considered critical infrastructure, and local agencies have to rely on private companies (like AT&amp;T, Verizon, Sprint) to ensure they are available during emergency events. &nbsp; But as we saw in the Sonoma Wildfires, these networks are susceptible, vulnerable to natural and man-made events, and may not be available during these emergency times.', 'The problem statement becomes, what is a solution for residents to still be able to communicate when the critical infrastructure is down?', 'There are applications that can create mesh networks &ndash; using peer to peer communications. &nbsp;These were used in Hong Kong (Sept. 2014) during the Umbrella Movement, as a way for protesters to organize themselves, without having to rely on the cellphone infrastructure. &nbsp;The application, FireChat, created an &ldquo;off the grid&rdquo; messaging system that didn&rsquo;t need towers to operate. &nbsp;But how can these types of tools be deployed and adopted by local residents and potentially government during emergency situations?'], %>
